\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Betweenness centrality is based on the number of shortest paths passing
 through a vertex.
 Vertices with a high betweenness play the role of connecting different
 groups.
 In the following formula, g
\begin_inset Formula $_{jik}$
\end_inset

 is all geodesics linking node j and node k which pass through node i.
 g
\begin_inset Formula $_{jk}$
\end_inset

 is the geodesic distance between the vertices of j and k.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula $C_{B}(n_{i})=\underset{j,k\neq i}{\Sigma}\frac{g_{jik}}{g_{jk}}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In social networks, vertices with high betweenness are the brokers and connector
s who bring others together 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-4"

\end_inset

.
 Being between means that a vertex has the ability to control the flow of
 knowledge between most others.
 Individuals with high betweenness are the pivots in the network knowledge
 flowing.
 The vertices with highest betweenness also result in the largest increase
 in typical distance between others when they are removed.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-3"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Closeness centrality on co-authorship networks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Closeness centrality 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-5"

\end_inset

 emphasizes the distance of a vertex to all others in the network through
 the geodesic distance from each vertex to all others.
 It is a measure of how long it will take for information to spread from
 a particular node 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-4"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{c}(n_{t})=\sum_{i=1}^{N}\frac{1}{d(n_{i},n_{j})}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $d(n_{i},n_{j})$
\end_inset

 is the distance from node 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to node 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{c}$
\end_inset

 is the closeness centrality.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-3"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Group centrality measures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-7"

\end_inset

, the degree centrality of a group is the number of actors outside the group
 that are connected to the member of that group.
 Different ties to the same actors by different group members are only counted
 once.
 The formula is described below: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Group\,degree\,centrality & = & |N(C)|\\
Normalized\,group\,degree\,centrality & = & \frac{|N(C)|}{|V|-|C|}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Where C is a group that is a subset of the set of vertices V, and N(C) denotes
 the set of all nodes that are not in C but connected to a member of C.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly group closeness and betweeness centralities are explored in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-6,key-7"

\end_inset

.
 These measures help us analyse the interdisciplinary nature of disciplines.
 
\end_layout

